The use of mactus is peculiar. It is generally employed in the voca- tive singular, macte, and when a deity is addressed signifies, ‘be thou honoured or glorified ;' examples are common in Cato de R. R. Thus (cap. 132), Iupiter dapalis . . . macte lzac illace dape pollucenda esto . . . macte vino inferio est0,· again (cap. 134), Iupiter, mactefircto esto; and (cap. 141), Mars pater. . macte lzt's suovetaurilibus lactentibus esto. When macte is addressed to a human being it is generally coupled with virtute* or some word expressing a good quality, and is a sort of complimentary formula implying a prayer that the person addressed may prosper and make constant additions to his stock of worth. That mactus implies the notion of making honourable additions to what we possess is seen in a line quoted from Lucilius by Serv. on Virg. AEn.
